What CHECKSUM Actually Does
Checksum converts row data into a numeric hash value.
SQL Server uses the values of columns to calculate a number.
If any column value changes, the number usually changes.
Two functions are involved:
Plain text
Copy code
BINARY_CHECKSUM   → row level hash
CHECKSUM_AGG      → combines hashes of all rows
Step 1 — Row Level Calculation
BINARY_CHECKSUM(*) takes all column values of a row and produces a number.
Example table
Plain text
Copy code
ID   NAME   AMOUNT
1    A      100
2    B      200
Query:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT ID, NAME, AMOUNT,
BINARY_CHECKSUM(ID, NAME, AMOUNT) AS row_checksum
FROM test_table
Example output
Plain text
Copy code
ID NAME AMOUNT row_checksum
1  A    100    438291
2  B    200    882173
Every row has its own checksum number.
Step 2 — Aggregate Checksum
Now SQL aggregates all row checksums using:
SQL
Copy code
CHECKSUM_AGG()
Example:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*))
FROM test_table
Example result
Plain text
Copy code
82344192
This single number represents all rows in the table.
What Happens When Data Changes
Example table
Plain text
Copy code
ID NAME AMOUNT
1  A    100
2  B    200
Row checksums:
Plain text
Copy code
Row1 → 438291
Row2 → 882173
Table checksum:
Plain text
Copy code
438291 + 882173 → aggregated hash → 82344192
Now change one value:
Plain text
Copy code
ID NAME AMOUNT
1  A    100
2  B    999
Row checksum becomes:
Plain text
Copy code
Row1 → 438291
Row2 → 774112
New aggregated checksum:
Plain text
Copy code
438291 + 774112 → new hash → 99128233
Checksum changed → data changed.
