How SQL Internally Calculates Checksum (Concept)
SQL takes column values and applies a hash algorithm.
Conceptually:
Plain text
Copy code
checksum = hash(col1 + col2 + col3 + ...)
Example row
Plain text
Copy code
ID=1
NAME='ABC'
AMOUNT=100
SQL internally converts values into binary form:
Plain text
Copy code
1 → binary
ABC → binary
100 → binary
Then applies hash logic → number.
Partition Level Example (Your Table)
Because your table uses report_date partitions, calculate checksum per partition.
Old table:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT
report_date,
CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*)) AS checksum_val
FROM dbo.cff_report
GROUP BY report_date
Result
Plain text
Copy code
report_date   checksum
2024-01-01    82392312
2024-02-01    22341123
New table:
SQL
Copy code
SELECT
report_date,
CHECKSUM_AGG(BINARY_CHECKSUM(*)) AS checksum_val
FROM dbo.cff_report_new
GROUP BY report_date
Both must match.
